    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Calcium Channel Blockers", content: "Calcium channel blockers (CCBs) inhibit L-type voltage-gated calcium channels in cardiac and vascular smooth muscle, reducing intracellular calcium concentration and thereby decreasing muscle contractility and vascular tone. Dihydropyridine CCBs (amlodipine, nifedipine) are primarily vascular selective, causing peripheral arteriolar vasodilation with minimal cardiac effects — they are first-line agents for hypertension and are useful in treating Raynaud's phenomenon and stable angina. Non-dihydropyridine CCBs (verapamil, diltiazem) have greater cardiac selectivity, reducing heart rate, slowing AV node conduction, and decreasing myocardial contractility — they are used for rate control in atrial fibrillation, supraventricular tachycardia, and angina but are contraindicated in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction and in combination with beta-blockers due to additive negative chronotropic and inotropic effects. Common side effects include peripheral edema (dihydropyridines), constipation (verapamil), headache, flushing, and dizziness — the nurse should monitor blood pressure, heart rate, and ECG, and educate patients to avoid grapefruit juice (inhibits CYP3A4, increasing drug levels)." },
