    diagnostics: ["Step 1: Order tTG-IgA AND total serum IgA simultaneously (total IgA identifies IgA-deficient patients who need IgG-based testing)","Step 2a: If tTG-IgA POSITIVE → refer for upper endoscopy with duodenal biopsies (4-6 biopsies from D2/D3, 1-2 from duodenal bulb due to patchy distribution)","Step 2b: If tTG-IgA NEGATIVE but total IgA LOW → order tTG-IgG and DGP-IgG (IgG-based tests)","Step 2c: If tTG-IgA NEGATIVE and total IgA NORMAL but high clinical suspicion → consider EMA-IgA or HLA-DQ2/DQ8 genotyping","Marsh classification of biopsies: grade 0 (normal) through grade 3c (total villous atrophy) guides diagnosis","HLA-DQ2/DQ8 genotyping: negative result essentially rules out celiac disease (>99% NPV); positive result does NOT confirm celiac (30-40% of general population carries these alleles)","Confirm patient is on gluten-containing diet at time of ALL testing — minimum 2 slices of bread daily for 6-8 weeks before testing"],
    management: ["Positive serology + positive biopsy = confirmed celiac → initiate strict lifelong gluten-free diet","Positive serology + negative biopsy = possible early celiac → repeat biopsy with additional samples, confirm gluten intake, consider HLA testing","Negative serology + clinical suspicion = check IgA levels; if IgA deficient, use IgG-based tests; if seronegative with high suspicion, consider endoscopy regardless","Refer to registered dietitian for comprehensive GFD education","Order baseline nutritional labs: CBC, ferritin, folate, B12, vitamin D, calcium, zinc, hepatic panel","Follow-up tTG-IgA in 6-12 months to assess dietary adherence (should normalize with strict GFD)","Consider repeat biopsy at 1-2 years to confirm mucosal healing in select cases"],
